Sweet — glad it’s mostly fixed. If you still see occasional flicker, that means a tiny bit of identity/state/paint churn is still slipping through. Below is a compact, battle-tested checklist plus precise fixes to stomp the last flickers out. Copy-paste the snippets where relevant.

Quick checklist — most common sneaky causes

Unstable props (inline objects, arrays, functions) passed to <Window> or page children.

Animation replay because hasEntered is per-mount, not per-window-id or persisted.

Position updates causing layout paints (using top/left vs transform: translate()).

Saving/loading race: layout load overwrites in-progress state after drag end.

Frequent state updates during drag (causes intermittent re-render spikes).

Keys changing (accidental re-keying on reorder).

Portals or focus changes that move DOM nodes around.

CSS transitions/layout thrash (expensive properties, forced reflow).

Hidden mount/unmount logs — something still unmounting occasionally.

Fast fixes & code snippets
1) Replace layout CSS top/left with transform for smooth low-cost moves

Use transform: translate(x, y) so the compositor handles it — no layout thrash.

.window {
  position: absolute;
  will-change: transform;
  transform: translate(var(--tx, 0px), var(--ty, 0px));
}


Update JS by setting CSS variables (no React re-render needed):

// useRef to hold DOM node
const nodeRef = useRef<HTMLDivElement | null>(null);

function setWindowTransform(x:number, y:number) {
  const n = nodeRef.current;
  if (!n) return;
  n.style.setProperty('--tx', `${x}px`);
  n.style.setProperty('--ty', `${y}px`);
}

2) Use requestAnimationFrame for live dragging (no state churn)

Keep the ephemeral drag state off React state.

const posRef = useRef({x:0,y:0});
const rafRef = useRef<number | null>(null);

function onPointerMove(e: PointerEvent) {
  posRef.current.x = e.clientX - offsetX;
  posRef.current.y = e.clientY - offsetY;
  if (rafRef.current === null) {
    rafRef.current = requestAnimationFrame(() => {
      setWindowTransform(posRef.current.x, posRef.current.y);
      rafRef.current = null;
    });
  }
}

3) Debounce persistence & avoid load race

When loading, ignore the first noisy save that can overwrite current drag:

const ignoreNextSaveRef = useRef(false);
useEffect(() => {
  // on mount, load saved layout
  const raw = localStorage.getItem('app:windowLayout');
  if (raw) {
    ignoreNextSaveRef.current = true;
    setWindows(JSON.parse(raw));
    setTimeout(() => (ignoreNextSaveRef.current = false), 50);
  }
}, []);

useEffect(() => {
  if (ignoreNextSaveRef.current) return;
  const id = setTimeout(() => {
    localStorage.setItem('app:windowLayout', JSON.stringify(windows));
  }, 250);
  return () => clearTimeout(id);
}, [windows]);

4) Make callbacks stable & avoid inline props

Always memoize handlers and any objects you pass down.

const closeWindow = useCallback((id:string) => {
  setWindows(prev => prev.filter(w => w.id !== id));
}, []);


If you must pass options, memoize them:

const options = useMemo(() => ({resizable: true, snap: false}), []);
<Window options={options} />

5) Persist hasEntered per-window (so animation never replays)

Keep seen-state keyed by windowId.

const seenRef = useRef<Record<string, boolean>>({});
function AnimatedSection({ windowId }) {
  const [hasEntered, setHasEntered] = useState(() => !!seenRef.current[windowId]);
  useEffect(() => {
    if (!hasEntered) {
      // trigger animation...
      seenRef.current[windowId] = true;
      setHasEntered(true);
    }
  }, []);
  ...
}

6) Ensure keys are stable

Mapping windows: key={win.id} not index or random.

7) Minimal render logging to find the offender

Drop temporary logs in mount/unmount and in Window render to catch which component actually remounts:

useEffect(() => {
  console.log('Portfolio mount', id);
  return () => console.log('Portfolio unmount', id);
}, []);


Run a short session and watch the console — if any mount/unmount appear while dragging other windows, you found the culprit.

Debug flow (do this in order — cheap & fast)

Open React Profiler, start recording. Drag windows until you see flicker. Inspect what mounted/unmounted or what rendered.

If profiler doesn’t show mounts, add the mount/unmount logs above for each suspect component.

Confirm transforms are used (inspect element computed style). If you see top/left, switch to transform.

Check localStorage events: add window.addEventListener('storage', e => console.log(e)); to see if some other tab/process is writing.

If flicker still happens, temporarily disable persistence and test. If flicker stops — it's a save/load race.

still flickers when you rearrange other nav/windows while Portfolio is open. That tells me Portfolio isn’t actually unmounting every time; something is still causing it to briefly hide/reset (visibility/paint churn or a tiny remount). Below I’ll give a targeted, no-nonsense checklist plus precise, drop-in code fixes you can apply right now to eliminate the last flicker — including a KeepAlive pattern, a stricter React.memo comparator for Window, and a few CSS/drag tweaks that stop paint/layout thrash.

Do these in order — each step is cheap and likely to fix the issue; stop when flicker disappears.

1) Quick certainty checks (1–2 mins)

Add these logs to confirm whether Portfolio actually unmounts or only hides:

In PortfolioPage:

useEffect(() => {
  console.log('[Portfolio] mount');
  return () => console.log('[Portfolio] unmount');
}, []);


If you see unmount, it’s a remount problem (keys / conditional render).
If you don't see unmount but you see the flicker, it's CSS/paint/visibility.

2) Keep the DOM mounted — Hide via CSS instead of conditional render (definitive)

Even if you think children are memoized, some parent prop or CSS may cause the content to reflow or become display:none. Definite way to stop flicker: mount Portfolio once and toggle visibility with opacity/visibility/pointer-events.

Create a tiny KeepAlive wrapper and use it for all pages:

// KeepAlive.tsx
import React, { useState, useEffect } from 'react';

export default function KeepAlive({ id, active, children }: { id: string; active: boolean; children: React.ReactNode }) {
  const [mounted] = useState(true); // mount once
  return (
    <div
      data-keepalive-id={id}
      aria-hidden={!active}
      style={{
        display: mounted ? 'block' : 'none', // always mounted, but this line remains block
        pointerEvents: active ? 'auto' : 'none',
        visibility: active ? 'visible' : 'hidden',
        opacity: active ? 1 : 0,
        transition: 'opacity .12s linear',
        willChange: 'opacity, transform',
      }}
    >
      {children}
    </div>
  );
}


Usage inside your Window render map (where you pass content):

// assume memoizedPages map exists
<Window key={win.id} {...win}>
  <KeepAlive id={win.id} active={win.id === currentActiveId}>
    {memoizedPages[win.id]}
  </KeepAlive>
</Window>


Why this helps: content never unmounts, so any layout/scroll/animations stay intact. Flicker caused by tiny remounts or display:none toggles goes away.

3) Stronger React.memo comparator on Window

Even small prop identity changes can trick memo. Use a custom comparator that only cares about truly rendering-changing props.

// Window.tsx
function areEqual(prev, next) {
  // bother only if these change
  if (prev.id !== next.id) return false;
  if (prev.minimized !== next.minimized) return false;
  if (prev.zIndex !== next.zIndex) return false;
  if (prev.position?.x !== next.position?.x || prev.position?.y !== next.position?.y) return false;
  // children are stable instances from memoized map; compare by reference
  if (prev.children !== next.children) return false;
  return true; // otherwise skip render
}

export default React.memo(WindowComponent, areEqual);


This prevents accidental renders when non-critical props (like ephemeral drag offsets on sibling windows) change.

4) Ensure movement & layout use transforms — not top/left

If any parent layout changes (like an adjacent nav changing size), and your windows use top/left, browser will reflow and may briefly hide or repaint. Use CSS variables + transform for smooth GPU-accelerated moves:

CSS:

.window {
  position: absolute;
  left: 0; top: 0; /* anchor */
  transform: translate(var(--tx, 0px), var(--ty, 0px));
  will-change: transform, opacity;
}


JS: update CSS variables on the element (via ref) using the rAF pattern you already have.

5) Avoid toggling display or moving nodes in DOM while dragging/sibling actions

Search code for anything that sets display: none or uses conditional rendering when nav actions happen. Replace with aria-hidden + opacity pattern (like KeepAlive above). Also check any portal logic that might re-parent content — avoid re-parenting while interacting.

6) Persist animation-seen state per-window (never replay)

If flicker is an animation replay, persist hasEntered keyed by windowId in a module-level map or localStorage:

const seenMap: Record<string, boolean> = {};

function AnimatedSection({ windowId }) {
  const [entered, setEntered] = useState(() => !!seenMap[windowId]);
  useEffect(() => {
    if (!entered) {
      // run enter animation
      seenMap[windowId] = true;
      setEntered(true);
    }
  }, []);
}


This ensures animations do not retrigger on incidental re-renders.

7) Check for parent CSS that toggles overflow/clip or applies filter / backdrop-filter

Filters and will-change on parent can cause repaint. If, for example, your top-level dashboard applies filter: blur(0) during drag or toggles overflow:hidden, that can cause a flicker. Temporarily remove such rules to test.

8) Defensive: force hardware compositing on the Portfolio container

If flicker is paint-related, forcing GPU compositing can help:

.portfolio-root {
  transform: translateZ(0);
  will-change: opacity, transform;
}


This is a last-resort performance trick. Use sparingly.

9) Debug to find the exact trigger (if still persists)

Run React Profiler while reproducing — look for renders or commits of PortfolioPage.

Add console.log in the Window comparator to see why it returns false (i.e., why it decided to render). Example:

function areEqual(prev, next) {
  const equal = /* comparator logic */;
  if (!equal) console.log('Window re-render reason', prev.id, {prev, next});
  return equal;
}


This will show the specific prop that flips when you rearrange navs.

10) Minimal keep-alive as fallback — preserve DOM + state

If you want a tiny plug-and-play fallback that guarantees Portfolio never hides, use this pattern in your Dashboard render:

// render all pages once, keep them hidden when not active
{Object.keys(memoizedPages).map(id => (
  <div key={id} style={{position:'absolute', inset:0, pointerEvents: currentId===id ? 'auto' : 'none',
    visibility: currentId===id ? 'visible' : 'hidden', opacity: currentId===id ? 1 : 0, transition:'opacity .12s'}}>
    {memoizedPages[id]}
  </div>
))}


Then your Window component simply positions the above container. This is brute-force but 100% effective.

